    <div class="container">
        <section id="lager" class="beer-type">
            <h2>Lager</h2>
            <p>Lager is a type of beer that is conditioned at low temperatures, usually around 2–10°C (36–50°F). It may be pale, golden, amber, or dark in color.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="ale" class="beer-type">
            <h2>Ale</h2>
            <p>Ale is a type of beer brewed using a warm fermentation method, resulting in a sweet, full-bodied, and fruity taste. Historically, the term referred to a drink brewed without hops.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="stout" class="beer-type">
            <h2>Stout</h2>
            <p>Stout is a dark, top-fermented beer with a number of variations, including dry stout, oatmeal stout, milk stout, and imperial stout. Stouts were traditionally the generic term for the strongest or stoutest porters.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="porter" class="beer-type">
            <h2>Porter</h2>
            <p>Porter is a dark style of beer originating in London, derived from well-hopped beers made from brown malt. The name originated from its popularity with street and river porters.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="ipa" class="beer-type">
            <h2>IPA (India Pale Ale)</h2>
            <p>IPA is a hoppy beer style within the broader category of pale ale. It is known for its strong hop flavor and higher alcohol content compared to other pale ales.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="wheat" class="beer-type">
            <h2>Wheat Beer</h2>
            <p>Wheat beer is usually top-fermented and brewed with a large proportion of wheat in addition to the usual barley. It often has a cloudy appearance due to the yeast and wheat proteins.</p>
        </section>

